Plan some winter (or summer) fun with a stay at this two bedroom Government Camp vacation rental! Perfect for a group of friends to share, this cozy and rustic getaway has an unbeatable location right on Government Camp Loop. Walk to Summit Ski Area, restaurants, and shops. From here, you'll be only minutes away from Mt. Hood Meadows, Timberline, and Mt. Hood Skibowl. Outdoor lovers take note - this area also offers unrivaled hiking, biking, and fishing, making Government Camp a truly year-round destination.

After climbing the stairs up to your mountain retreat, you'll be rewarded with a comfortable living area with an open living room and kitchen. There's a wood stove for keeping all warm and toasty and plenty of room for everyone to spread out and relax.

The dining table is near the front deck, providing a forested view for meals or a game of cards after dinner. If you do want to stay in for dinner, the full kitchen has everything you'll need for any meal - from coffee and pancakes in the morning to a heart vegetable lasagna at night. And if you need to soak the dishes, you can always have a mug of hot cocoa in front of the fire.

Both bedrooms have twin-over-Queen bunk beds and dressers. The full bathroom has a lot of counter space for toiletries and a tub/shower combo. Altogether, this Mt. Hood cabin rental will sleep up to six guests (four adults).

This is the lower level of a duplex, and there is a shared laundry room with a washer and dryer available. From here, you can easily walk to the Govy General Store for dinner supplies or a bottle of wine. And if you don't feel like cooking, Ice Axe Grill, Charlie's Mountain View, Glacier Haus Bistro & Pizza, and other eateries are all within a couple of blocks... and although you do have a kitchen, you may find yourself having a Pork Belly Sandwich at Glacier Haus a couple of days in a row!

In ski season, Mt. Hood Skibowl, Timberline Lodge, and Mt. Hood Meadows are all just a quick drive away. And right from town, you'll be able to pick up cross-country and snowshoeing trails. Also nearby are the Mt. Hood Meadows Nordic Center, Trillium Lake Loop, and the Teacup Lake Nordic Trail.

Summer brings wildflowers, scenic trails through the Mt. Hood National Forest, and even mountain climbing at Timberline Lodge mid-April through mid-June. There's a mountain bike park at Mt. Hood Skibowl and kayaking and canoeing on Trillium, Frog, Clear, and Timothy Lakes. There's always something to do here!

Truly a four season destination, you'll feel right at home at this Government Camp getaway, whether you spend your time hiking green mountain trails or snowshoeing around a winter wonderland.

